			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Epic 1.5 - The Code of Silence Experience, Part 3<a name="68278"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 27 04 11:01 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Our third &quot;epic night&quot; and we started the evening with 3 groups of people but no warriors.  This can be a serious crippling problem for us.  We are not a large guild and we are pre-Time, having only been in the elementals for a couple of months and lacking any Elemental god kills.  We have 3 warrior mains and none of the three has any interest at all in pursuing their epic 1.5 so it is hard to get them excited about epic nights.
<br />

<br />
We started the night attempting the final kill for a druid.  This fight is in Kithicor and the starting mob for this is the Blackened Treant.  It was a straight up melee mob and not that tough for a 9K hit point paladin.  But when it dies, it pops out 10 Blackened brances which are nasty little treants that are unmezzable.  They just slaughtered our healers and we began working them down one or two at a time but they were overwhelming us.  I finally kited two of them off -- I was down to 384 HP at that moment -- and folks began rezzing and regrouping.  I managed to zone out to lose my two and came back to find the raid killing the last of them but leaving one up and rooted until we got thoroughly re-buffed and ready.  When we were set, we killed that last one to spawn the Blackened Dryad.  This is a mob with a nasty AE debuff -- Whithered Glare or something like that -- which lowers your str, dex, and attack by 500 each.  The thing checks poison at -300 so even with resists maxed out by POV it tends to get through eventually.  It is curable, but that takes time.  We eventually wiped to the Dryad -- a non-defensive tank just sucks up too much mana since the attack buff really slows down your melee DPS and that was about 75% of our DPS.  The dryad eventually despawns and that shuts down the event for 2 hours so we moved on.
<br />

<br />
Shortly after this, a warrior did join us so, having learned that all my dragon fights are multi-group affairs for a pre-time guild, we headed to Stonebrunt to take on the Dire Panda and the Mountain Dragon.  This actually was the easiest battle of the night.  The dragons do have a lot of hit points, but on this one, at least, the AE is a minor issue.  It is chromatic but the resist adjust is small.  My group, main tank and clerics, only got hit with it one time the entire fight and resisted all the others.  So I have my mountain dragon crystal.
<br />

<br />
Next stop was Natimbi for a ranger battle.  This fight took place on one of the platforms off to the southwest corner of the zone and it is wise to make sure everyone has levitate for this fight.  It's a long drop off the sides.  I do not remember the names of the mobs - Allakhazam doesn't list them and I am too lazy to go to a ranger site.  The starting spawn is a named Mastruq model with two elementals out in front of him.  The named is tethered and the two elementals can be fought without engaging him.  He has a fire-based AE, it is resistable but will probably hit now and then.  It is a DD up to 1500 top damage.  During the fight, he spawns a number of elementals -- think they were timed, not tied to his health -- and one named elemental.  They are all mezzable so keep them locked down and go after the mastruq.  Then, clear the non-named elementals and leave the named for last.  This guy is actually NOT killed, but rather beaten into submission.  If you kill him, the ranger has failed this part.  We had to call everyone off when he got to 30% and then the ranger tanked and we nibbled him down to about 4% health and then an emote goes off, the ranger hails, and gets the drop he needs.  The elemental then despawned and he dropped a chest which had a nice caster ring.  This fight was done with 22 people, I believe and we had one or two deaths, but otherwise it just requires coordination and people listening to instructions.  I have heard of much better equipped raids than ours wiping to this but it could only have been due to bad coordination and people breaking mezzes.  The mobs didn't hit that hard or do that much damage.
<br />

<br />
Looking ahead, my guild knows I have 7 more multi-group fights and they seem very supportive.  I don't think I have properly impressed on them that without 30+ people we cannot do DN fight #2, but Code seems to excel at fights that require complex coordination.  We suck at zerg mobs because we never have the numbers for that, so I hold out hope that the main restriction on DN #2 for me will be getting enough folks to deal with Vesthon himself.  Anyway, I will probably do the other 3 dragons and then DN #1 over the next couple of months, then we will see if I can scare together an off-night raid for the other DN fight.
<br />

<br />
Or maybe EQ2 will render it all moot.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
